    <div class="card-info" id="cardInfo">
    <h2>David Bruce</h2>
    <p><strong>Lifetime:</strong> 1855â€“1931</p>
    <p><strong>Title:</strong> Pioneer of Veterinary Microbiology</p>
    <p><strong>Achievements:</strong> David Bruce, a Scottish microbiologist and pathologist, made significant contributions to microbiology, particularly in the study of infectious diseases. His most notable discovery was identifying *Trypanosoma brucei*, the parasitic protozoan responsible for African trypanosomiasis, also known as sleeping sickness. In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, while working in what is now Zimbabwe, Bruce traced the disease to the tsetse fly (*Glossina*) as its vector, establishing the connection between the parasite, the fly, and the disease. This breakthrough was crucial in understanding how the disease spread and led to efforts in controlling tsetse fly populations to prevent transmission. Additionally, Bruce identified *Brucella* bacteria, the causative agent of brucellosis (Malta fever), which affects both humans and livestock. His research on bacterial and parasitic diseases helped advance medical microbiology and epidemiology, influencing strategies for disease prevention and control worldwide.</p>
    <p><strong>Legacy:</strong> David Bruce's legacy in microbiology is significant, particularly for his contributions to the understanding of infectious diseases. He is best known for identifying *Trypanosoma brucei*, the parasite responsible for African trypanosomiasis (sleeping sickness), a disease transmitted by the tsetse fly. His research also led to crucial insights into brucellosis, a bacterial infection caused by *Brucella* species, which was later named in his honor. Bruce's meticulous investigations into disease transmission mechanisms laid the groundwork for modern epidemiology and tropical medicine. His work not only advanced microbiology but also helped in the development of strategies to combat vector-borne diseases, ultimately saving countless lives.</p>
</div>


    <script>
        const card = document.getElementById('gameCard');
        const cardInfo = document.getElementById('cardInfo');

        card.addEventListener('click', () => {
            card.classList.toggle('is-flipped');
            cardInfo.classList.toggle('visible');
        });
    </script>

